---
import PageLayout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import SectionHeading from '~/components/ui/SectionHeading.astro';
import TrustStrip from '~/components/sections/TrustStrip.astro';
import Button from '~/components/ui/Button.astro';
import { site } from '~/lib/site';
---
<PageLayout
  title="About"
  description="Elera Construction is a GTA residential renovation company founded on 10+ years of new-construction experience with Toronto's leading developers."
  canonicalPath="/about"
>
  <section class="bg-cream pt-16 pb-12 md:pt-24 md:pb-16">
    <div class="container-x grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 md:gap-16 items-center">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">About Elera</p>
        <h1 class="mt-4 text-4xl md:text-6xl font-extrabold leading-tight">Built by people who built for the builders.</h1>
        <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-muted max-w-prose">
          Elera Construction was founded by {site.founder}, who spent over a decade on the build side of new low-rise residential construction for some of Toronto's largest developers. The renovation work we do for homeowners today follows the same playbook: detailed planning, professional project management, and the supplier relationships that make trade pricing on premium materials possible.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="aspect-[4/5] bg-hairline/60 grid place-items-center rounded-sm">
        <span class="text-sm text-muted">[Founder photo placeholder]</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <TrustStrip />

  <section class="py-24 md:py-32 bg-paper">
    <div class="container-x grid lg:grid-cols-12 gap-12">
      <div class="lg:col-span-5">
        <SectionHeading
          eyebrow="THE STORY"
          heading="Ten years on the developer side."
        />
      </div>
      <div class="lg:col-span-7 prose max-w-none text-ink leading-relaxed space-y-4">
        <p>
          Most renovation contractors learn the trade by renovating houses. {site.founder} learned it by building them — from foundations up, under warranty programs of Toronto's largest residential developers. New-construction work runs on a different discipline than typical renovation: detailed drawings before anyone picks up a hammer, written change orders, milestone-based payment tied to verifiable construction stages, and a quality bar enforced by both the city and the developer's warranty arm.
        </p>
        <p>
          After ten-plus years of that work, the patterns became obvious. The contractors who excelled were not necessarily the most talented tradespeople — they were the ones who planned tightly, communicated clearly, and protected their schedules from the chaos that scope changes introduce. The contractors who struggled were almost always victims of vague scope and ad-hoc change management.
        </p>
        <p>
          Elera Construction exists to bring that discipline to residential renovation in the GTA. Same standards. Same documentation. Same supplier accounts. The only thing that changes is the project — instead of building a new home from scratch for a developer, we renovate your home for you.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-24 md:py-32 bg-ink text-cream">
    <div class="container-x grid lg:grid-cols-12 gap-12">
      <div class="lg:col-span-5">
        <p class="eyebrow text-midnight-soft">THE SUPPLIER ADVANTAGE</p>
        <h2 class="mt-3 text-3xl md:text-5xl font-extrabold leading-tight">Trade pricing you can't get at retail.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="lg:col-span-7 space-y-4 text-cream/80 leading-relaxed">
        <p>
          The cabinetry, tile, stone, hardwood, and fixture suppliers who priced thousands of square feet of new construction for {site.founder}'s developer clients price the same way for us today.
        </p>
        <p>
          Retail showrooms operate on a different margin model — they have to. Trade pricing through our supplier network is typically 25–40% below the equivalent retail-showroom quote for the same product, often the same SKU. On a $80,000 kitchen, that's $10K–$20K that doesn't get spent at the showroom.
        </p>
        <p>
          We pass that pricing through directly. It's why we don't publish package pricing the way retail kitchen companies do — we'd rather show you the actual materials at the actual price than mark up the materials to hit a marketing number.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-24 md:py-32 bg-paper">
    <div class="container-x">
      <SectionHeading
        eyebrow="VALUES"
        heading="What we hold ourselves to."
        align="center"
        class="mb-16"
      />
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-extrabold text-ink">No vague lump sums.</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-muted leading-relaxed">Every quote is line-itemed. Labour separate from materials. Allowances called out. Change orders in writing. If we can't put a number on it, we won't pretend to.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-extrabold text-ink">One point of contact.</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-muted leading-relaxed">You text or email the same person from consultation through final walkthrough. No call-centre handoffs, no "let me check with the office."</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-xl font-extrabold text-ink">Warranty in writing.</h3>
          <p class="mt-3 text-muted leading-relaxed">Two-year workmanship warranty on everything we build, signed and dated as part of your closeout package. If it fails, we come back.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-24 bg-cream">
    <div class="container-x text-center">
      <SectionHeading
        eyebrow="READY TO TALK?"
        heading="Free consultation. No pressure."
        align="center"
      />
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3 justify-center">
        <Button href="/contact" variant="primary">Book a consultation →</Button>
        <Button href="/projects" variant="secondary">See our work</Button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</PageLayout>
